No Internet Connectivity After Manual DNS Configuration
Issue

A user reported having no internet connectivity after manually changing their network settings. Public websites such as Google, the company intranet, and the finance portal were all unreachable.

Business Impact

The user was unable to access any online resources, preventing them from performing their daily work.

Troubleshooting Performed
User restarted the computer.
Confirmed other users on the same network had internet access.
User mentioned they had manually configured the DNS server to 8.8.8.8 after following online advice to improve internet speed.
Resolution
Connected to the user's computer using Remote Support.
Opened Control Panel.
Navigated to Network and Sharing Center.
Opened the active network adapter properties.
Opened Internet Protocol Version 4 (TCP/IPv4) settings.
Changed the DNS configuration from a manually specified DNS server back to Obtain DNS server address automatically.
Applied the changes.
Confirmed internet connectivity was restored.
Root Cause

The user had manually configured the DNS settings, which prevented the workstation from correctly resolving domain names on the corporate network.

Prevention
Advise users not to modify network settings without IT guidance.
Use the organization's recommended DNS configuration.
Document approved network settings for end users.
Skills Demonstrated
DNS troubleshooting
Windows network configuration
Remote support
TCP/IP configuration
End-user support
Lessons Learned

When a user can no longer access any websites after changing network settings, check the DNS configuration. Incorrect DNS settings can prevent name resolution even when the network connection itself is working.
